description.plain:
KALEO (“the voice” in Hawaiian) is an Icelandic alternative rock band established in 2012. The band originally consisted of Jökull “Julius Son” Júlíusson (vocals and guitar), Davíð Antonsson (percussion and vocals), Daníel Ægir Kristjánsson (bass) and Rubin Pollock (guitar and vocals). They gained their initial fame with “Vor í vaglaskógi,” which is now included on the original soundtrack to the TV Series Trapped.
Their fame continued with singles like “Way Down We Go” and “All the Pretty Girls,” but mostly with their song “No Good,” which appeared in the HBO series, Vinyl.

After four years, Julius Son took charge of the new KALEO project and released Surface Sounds in mid 2020.

description.plain:
“Way Down We Go” is a song by The Icelandic rock band Kaleo, released as the second single for their first studio album A/B.

Two music videos have been released to accompany the song. The first shows the band performing the song in the magma chamber of dormant volcano Thrihnukagigur, giving it somewhat a literal meaning.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9WIU5NN1Q0g

A year later a music video with the band performing along with the original studio recording in front of projector screens was released.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0-7IHOXkiV8

description.plain:
Vor í Vanglaskógi is the eight song in Kaleo´s second album, A/B.

It has a slow rhythm, same as in All the Pretty Girls, Automobile, Save Yourself, and i Can´t Go On Without You.

This song is originally written, and is sang in Icelandic, but, as not many people knows to speak that language, here´s the translation of the song.

Also, when you translate the title to english, it literally means “Spring in Vaglaskogur”. Vaglaskogur is a forest located in Iceland, which you can actually go and visit for yourself.

description.plain:
Sumptuously seductive, All The Pretty Girls propelled the Icelandic band to a global stage in the spring of 2014.



On the band’s website, Frontman JJ Juliusson describes the hit single as “a very delicate song…[that] seemed to speak to a lot of people.”

JJ also credits the song for Kaleo’s seemingly over-night success:

From there everything started to happen. We got contacted from other places: managers, labels, publishers—they all went crazy over one night.

description.plain:
Described as a “gritty, Jack White–esque blues-rock anthem”, “No Good” was featured on the original soundtrack to HBO’s new series Vinyl and later appeared in its 6th episode, Cyclone

JJ Julius Son told Rolling Stone,

“When we heard about Vinyl, we loved the vibe and jumped at the chance to contribute to it. As a huge fan of both Mick Jagger and Martin Scorsese, it’s an honor for me personally to be a part of project that they’ve created.”
